{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636916"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:35:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:35:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17612"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17612","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17612"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10326"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78529"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10326"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17612"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63870"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7317"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24159"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26007"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78529"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe superficial layer of back muscles consists of several important muscles that are primarily involved in movements of the upper limb and scapula. One of these muscles is the trapezius.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the anatomical attachments of this muscle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Extends from mastoid process to T8 vertebra","Extends from C2 to T8 vertebra","Extends from external occipital protuberance to T12 vertebra","Extends from C4 to T10 vertebra","Extends from occiput to T6 vertebra"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etrapezius muscle extends from the external occipital protuberance to T12 vertebra \u003C/strong\u003E(Image). It is a large, flat, triangular muscle that forms the most superficial muscle layer of the upper back. Its fibres attach to the external occipital protuberance, ligamentum nuchae, and spinous processes of cervical and thoracic vertebrae.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtends from mastoid process to T8 vertebra\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes incorrect superior and inferior attachments for trapezius\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtends from C2 to T8 vertebra\u003C/strong\u003E - This misses the superior attachment at the skull and describes too short an inferior extent\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtends from C4 to T10 vertebra\u003C/strong\u003E - This misses the superior attachment at the skull\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtends from occiput to T6 vertebra\u003C/strong\u003E - While the superior attachment is correct, the inferior extent is too short\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe trapezius muscle has three functional parts: upper (elevates scapula), middle (retracts scapula), and lower (depresses scapula). Together with other superficial back muscles, it plays a crucial role in shoulder girdle movements.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The superficial muscles of the back include trapezius, latissimus dorsi, levator scapulae, and rhomboids.","Trapezius is a large, flat, triangular muscle that extends from the skull to the lower thoracic vertebrae.","The trapezius has three functional parts: upper (elevation), middle (retraction), and lower (depression) of the scapula."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cTrapezius Muscle\u201d by Anatomography is licensed under\u00a0Creative Commons\u00a0Attribution-Share Alike 2.1 jp Unported\u00a0license. (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.1/jp/deed.en). \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Trapezius_lateral3.png\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63870"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17612"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21376"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21376"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/GGkdlB2d8oesXe1Z41B16dLqMuwcN4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/GGkdlB2d8oesXe1Z41B16dLqMuwcN4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":640}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63870"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T10:00:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T10:01:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10326"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78529"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"d